Brautigan’s poem *"The Burning of Rome"* (from *The Pill Versus the Springhill Mine Disaster*) reimagines Nero’s alleged role in the Great Fire of Rome as a grotesque, predatory act. The "evil Sherman" likely references Nero’s military title (*imperator*), while the "clothes with no childhood" evoke his decadent, detached rule. This interpretation aligns with the poem’s dark, surreal critique of power and destruction.
